The sun was shining and first- and fifth-graders got to take their own pine tree seedlings home to plant in their own yards. The 26th annual event took place in the Brian Gregg Memorial Park in Newtown Borough.

James Stiteler of the Pennsylvania Department of Conservation and Natural Resources read the announcment. The sun was shining. the children were happy and everyone enjoyed the fresh air.

The occassion was the annual Arbor Day celebration when Newtown was named a Tree City USA. Jennifer Abramson and Karen Waitkus co-chaired the event. "I feel honored to play my part in contributing such a worthwhile tradition." said Abramson.

title: Langhorne's skydiving mayor makes perfect landing
description: Langhorne Borough Mayor Chris Blaydon took to the skies on April 29 to do something he's never done before - jump out of a plane. Will he ever do it again? Watch and see.

title: Grey Nun Academy celebrates Science Day in Yardley
description: For students at Grey Nun Academy. Science Day was a time for exploration and learning. One of the stations included observation of worms. The teacher pointed out where the wiggly thing's hearts were. Another highlight of the day was climbing aboard the green Hybrid SEPTA bus.

description: Bud Baldwin and Tom Cino. both Upper Makefield Township supervisors. were enjoying the sunshine at the 2nd Annual Earth Day Celebration. Kids were making birdhouses. Teenagers were distributing tree seedlings. And there was even a red hawk 'visiting' from the AARK Rehabilitation Center.

description: The ewes at the Thompson Neely House were sheared and to the sheer delight of their caregivers. many people stopped by for the occasion when the historic home was open to the public for the first time since layoffs at Washington Crossing Historic Park. Nancy and Samantha Heyrich. two of the sheep's volunteer caregivers. said all nine sheep were happy to lose their coats.

description: Retiree Dave Yantz of Yardley dressed in a Colonial costume as he does every other year to mark Colonial Day at Makefield Elementary School. He started the tradition because he believes in hands-on eduation. Yantz worked for Pennsbury School District for 34 years --  18 of those years were at Makefield.

Gilbert's design depicts George Washington crossing the Delaware River. Lynskey drew five American soldiers. "I'm happy to have helped out an important part of the community." he said.

description: Fred Caldwell of Churchville. a member of the Guardians of the National Cemetery. was one of many veterans to attend a patriotic ceremony held at the Netown Middle School. Caldwell said the Guardians led the way in assuring a veterans cemetery would be estqablished in Washington Crossing. Proudly wearing his VFW hat with many military pins on it. he said the program was a moment in history.

title: Pennsbury Senior Prom deemed "Best" in America
description: Elegant young women in sleek gowns and young men dressed to the tee in tuxedos hit the red carpet at the Pennsbury Senior Prom on Saturday. May 15. Erin Meyers of New Hope was the carriage driver for Conrad Donnelly. 19. and Kristine Kelly. 17. Sixteen-year-old Lewis Sears. a sophomore. hammed it up in an Elvis Presley costume. Reader's Digest named Pennsbury's prom the best in the country.

title: VFW 6393 retires American flags in solemn ceremony
description: As the flames reacherd higher. attendees at the annual flag retirement ceremony each placed an old American flag in the fire. Russ Davidson. the next VFW commander in the Yardley area. said. "This is the proper way in which we retire the greatest symbol of our nation that no longer is of service to our nation."

title: Christopher Desmond leads flag retirement ceremony
description: Christopher Desmond. outgoing commander of the VFW 6393 in Lower Makefield Township. led a solemn ceremony when old American flags were officially "retired" May 15 on the local VFW grounds on Newtown-Yardley Road. For VFW member John Medvedis. the ceremony is a way to remember servicemen who are missing in action or who have died for their country.

title: Skateboard board park to be ready this summer
description: Mike Iaplucci. a leader with the ad-hoc Skateboard Park Committee. said Jim Worthington. owner of the Newtown Athletic Club has donated $10.000 to help pay the tab for the Newtown Township skateboard park. Iaplucci said the park should be ready for use ithis summer. Skateboarding. he said. "fills a need" for kids who are not in organized sports. His son. Angelo. loves skateboarding.

description: A motion to stop teachers' union members from wearing protest buttons and lanyards in school was approved by the Pennsbury School Board on May 20. Union president George Miller said the his members would take them off if the school board gets rid of its negotiator. The school board wants to freeze salaries while the union wants an increase of 5.46 percent in the first year.

The parade is organized this year by the VFW Post 6393. Indeed. 95-year-old Danny Quill. a World War II veteran. has become a local celebrity.

She took her case again to Upper Makefield Township leaders. asking for a state hearing on the matter. Rep. Scott Petri says he believes a Senate hearing will take place. "It's about time we get some attention from Harrisburg on this specific site. he said.

description: Mike Iaplucci is one of several parents. who is working to establish a skateboard park in Newtown Township. Iaplucci. whose son. Angelo is a skateboarder. said. June 5 from 4 to 6 p.m. between Durham Road and Silo Drive on North Sycamore Street.

description: The ceremonial ribbon was snipped Saturday. June 26 to mark the opening of the Morrisville Dog Park at Philadelphia and Delmorr avenues in Morrisville Borough. July 7 where county officials addressed many dog owners. Alice Amareld of Richboro brought "Scout." a seven-year-old Maltese. Tettemer has not officially 'retired' from the fire service. "I still go to fires every day." he said. "I finished in the top ten last year. I'm in the top ten so far this year. I don't miss many day fires."

The dog park has a solar-powered card system. Applications for card access are available in person at the park office at 901 E. Bridgetown Pike. Langhorne. PA 19047. A current dog license and rabies vaccination are required.

Veterans march down Edgewood Road in LMT
description: Kevin Treiber. chairman of the Lower Makefield Township Veterans Committee. told the Yardley News that this year's Veterans' Day Parade may not have happened had it not been for donations. Greg Caiola. vice chairman of the Lower Makefield Township Board of Supervisors. said $4.800 was raised by the community to hold the event. The parade was cut from the township budget due to financial issues.

title: Mansion Inn Fire in New Hope
Bell tolls at national veterans cemetery
description: UPPER MAKEFIELD -- Two minutes of silence descended on the Washington Crossing National Cemetery Thursday morning. Then a bell tolled 11 times signifying the moment World War I formally ended with the signing of the Armistice at the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month of 1918.

title: Fred Caldwell: 'We celebrated all veterans'
description: U.S. Navy BN2 Fred Caldwell of Churchville said. "We had a very beautiful ceremony to celebrate the arrival of this cemetery. and we celebrated all veterans present and deceased. This should be an annual function and it will grow as the cemetery grows." Caldwell was talking about the Inaugural Veterans Day Observance at Washington Crossing National Cemetery on Thursday. Nov. 11.

title: Yardley Business Association showcase draws 100
description: The Yardley Business Assocation (YBA) hosted the 2nd Annual Holiday Business Showcase at the Yardley Community Centre on Nov. 13.  Many of the attendees were participating in Landmark Town's "Passport to Main Street." Yardley Borough was one of four stops on the trolly trip. Peter Toft of the YBA directed folks from Buttonwood Park to the centre. About 100 people attended the downtown event.

title: Should Obamacare be repealed?
description: Shoppers at McCaffrey's Supermarket in Yardley were part of our weekly feature. Word on the Street. The question asked was: "Should Obamacare be repealed?" One woman said 'Yes' because she likes to have healthcare choices. One man said 'No' because 40 million Americans are without health insurance.

title: Danny Quill receives letter from President Obama
description: It's not everyday you get a letter from President Obama. But. Danny Quill. a World War II veteran. did. Danny. who lives in Morrisville Borough. is practically a celebrity in the area. He boasts that he is the oldest VFW and American Legion member in Yardley. A framed copy of the letter was presented to him at the Veterans Day ceremony in Yardley Borough. On Feb. 15. 2011. Danny will turn 96.

title: How can teenage substance abuse be prevented?
description: Seven people on State Street in Newtown were asked what can be done to prevent teenage substance abuse. Continued education was one of the ideas suggested by some folks. One resident said being connected with your children is important. A teenager recommended the formation of a group "where kids can go and do fun stuff that's not drug related...so they don't have to resort to drugs..."

title: The Great Gobbler of Bucks County
description: One thousand turkeys are a lot of turkeys. That's how many are sold in April at Davis Feed Mills in Rushland. They arrive when they are a day old. There's a three-turky minimum. Some folks will buy 20 baby turkeys. which when grown. will supply a whole family with Thanksgiving dinner. Other turkeys remain as pets. The Great Gobbler Contest is held in November. This year's winner is Ken Warfield.

title: Quarry Quagmire: fast loud trucks
What is your favorite all-time movie?
description: We asked shoppers at McCaffrey's Supermarket in Yardley what their favorite all-time movie is. One woman said "The Notebook" because it depicts love at its best. One man said he likes the original "Time Machine" because it is thought-provoking. Starring Amy Patterson. Joseph Norton. Howard Spencer. Louis Somma. George Garrison and Kristi Guglietta.

title: Yardley wishes shared with Santa at Old Library
description: A star shined brightly above Yardley Borough as about 250 folks. including pint-sized people. turned out to see the illlumination of the official Christmas tree and visit with Santa Claus on Friday. Nov. 26. Among the kids who came to see him were Paige and Liam Halligan; Carly Michel; Daniel Roach and Ciara Rago. Even Lainey Angove. 14 months old. was there.

title: James Murray writes Images of Morrisville
description: Images of Morrisville. a book by Morrisville native James Murray. is on sale in four locations in Morrisville: The Squirrel's Nest on West Bridge Street. Cunningham's Hardware Store on Pennsylvania Avenue. Burns Pharmacy on Pennsylvania Avenue and Historic Summerseat at Legion and Hillcrest avenues. It was once the home of two signers of the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution.

title: Should NASA decrease its astronaut corps?
description: We asked shoppers on State Street in Newtown Borough whether NASA's 64-member astronaut corps should be decreased. One woman said the corps should be increased. Another one said she thought NASA should tighten its belt like others have.

title: Holiday rush: Candy cane hunt in Newtown
description: Here's a new way to look at the holiday rush. Newtown Township Parks and Recreation held its annual Candy Cane Hunt. which sent kids scrambling across the fields at Roberts Ridge Park in search of the hard candy holiday treat.

title: Pennington Holiday Walk 2010
Holiday Shopping: Witch List
Tim Lohan/Eagle Fire Co/New Hope
MediMedia collects bikes for Toys for Tots
description: Bundled up in winter coats. warm gloves and hats. employees of MediMedia in Lower Makefield Corporate Center South braved the bitter windy air Dec. 14 to participate in the annual U.S. Marines Reserve Toys for Tots program. Over 600 toys and 900 bikes were collected. A motorcade and caravan included the Frathernal Order of Police (F.O.P.) Pa. State Lodge and the Lower Makefield Township Police.

title: Joe Hogan salutes audience at Wasthington Crossing
description: Joe Hogan. vice president of the Guardians of the National Cemetery. the official support committee for the cemetery. saluted. "I thank everyone of the people who stepped up to the plate." he said about the folks who turned out to place wreaths on the gravesites of veterans at Washington Crossing. Hogan said 1500 wreaths were donated for the Wreaths Across America ceremony held Dec. 11.

title: Wreaths placed at Washington Crossing cemetery
description: At a solemn ceremony on Dec. 11. evergreen wreaths with bright red bows were laid at the base of a flagpole and at the more than 1.500 gravesites at the Washington Crossing National Cemetery. The event marked the first time the Wreaths Across America  project took place there. Ray Reinard. a Boy Scout in Troop 99. placed a wreath on a veteran's grave. "I felt honored to be a part of this."

title: Pennsbury Falconairs perform at board meeting
description: The Pennsbury Falconairs womens choir performed at the Pennsbury School Board meeting on Monday. Dec. 6. The group is a contender in this year's WBEB (B101) Christmas Choir Competition

title: Limited-access boat ramp dedicated at Crossing
description: Officials from the Delaware River Joint Toll Bridge Commission joined leaders of Washington Crossing Historic Park and the Upper Makefield Fire Company in dedicating a limited-access boat ramp at Washington Crossing Park. The commission presentedthe keys to the ramp to the park and emergency officials who will use it for river rescues and the annual Christmas Day re-enactment.

title: World Trade Center remnant arrives at Eagle
description: With sirens wailing. a steel remnant from the World Trade Center arrived at the New Hope Eagle Fire Company on Dec. 18. a gift to the Delaware Valley Fire Museum. Inc. from the Terry Farrell Firefighters Fund. The steel beam is being dedicated to the memory of those 343 brave firemen and other first responders who entered the twin towers and did not come out alive.

title: Washington and troops rehearse for crossing
description: The general and his troops row across the Delaware to New Jersey in preparation for the Christmas crossing at Washington Crossing Historic Park.

title: Winter Wonderland
description: Yardley's Lake Afton becomes even more picturesque as skaters take advantage of the winter weather on Saturday. Dec. 18. Starring Jeff Shapiro. Cole Long. Adam Shapiro. Gary Rago. Ciara Rago and Alana Rago.

title: Word on the Street; Cliff Lee back with Phils?
description: How will the Phillies do with Cliff Lee back? This question was posed along Newtown Borough's State Street on Sunday. Dec. 19. Many local residents said the Phillies' pitching staff would lead to their success. Starring: Eddie Legoff. Dan Dinneen. Steve Ross. Pat Dunleavy and Richard Shusterman.

title: Word on the Street; How can we help the homeless?
description: For this Word on the Street we asked shoppers at McCaffery's Supermarket in Yardley what should be done to help the homeless on Saturday. Dec. 11. One shopper suggested increased awareness of the issue. others said more job opportunities would make a difference. Starring: Stephanie Schrader. Elliot Kerachsky. Mike Holowienka. Katie Smith. Randy Bannerman and Patricia Sims.

title: Word on the Street: Christmas too materialistic?
description: This week's Word on the Street was asked on Yardley's Main Street. Wednesday. Dec. 22. The majority of residents said Christmas is too materialistic. but many argued that the true spirit of Christmas is something very different. One woman said that spending time with her family was the real meaning of Christmas. while another said that it is our culture that makes Christmas materialistic.

title: Unions protest possible layoffs in Newtown
description: Close to 200 people. many of them township police officers. firefighters and municipal workers jammed into the Newtown Township building meeting room to protest possible layoffs on Wednesday Dec. 22.

title: Bucks pounded by snow; New Hope parties
Washington crosses Delaware in annual reenactment
description: The Friends of Washington Crossing Park and the Pennsylvania and Museum Commission hosted the 58th Annual Washington Crossing Reenactment on Christmas Day.

title: Word on the Street: New Year's Resolution?
description: What's you New Year's resolution? We put this question to six people on Newtown's State Street on Thursday. Dec. 30. 2010. One person said she would try to have a book published and another wanted to spend more time with her children.

title: Newtown Township property taxes will not rise
description: Amidst talk of potential layoffs or concessions from two unions. the Newtown Township Board of Supervisors voted 3-2 on Dec. 29 to adopt its 2011 $10.48 million budget and decided not to raise taxes. The budget's adoption came without any decision from the two unions who have been pressed by the board to make concessions or face layoffs. Board Chairman Rob Ciervo said he hopes for a compromise.

title: Hundreds celebrate New Year's Eve in Newtown
description: As the final few hours of 2010 ticked away. several hundred people enjoyed music. fun and revelry at First Night Newtown. A portion of the proceeds from this year's event will benefit the Newtown Township D.A.R.E. program. which teaches students the dangers of drugs and alcohol.

title: Mike Fitzpatrick holds first town meeting
description: Congressman-elect Mike Fitzpatrick hosted his first town meeting. "The key issue addressed tonight has to do with overspending in the federal government and bringing the federal deficit and national debt under control." he said. Scott Piazza asked if Fitzpatrick would support repealing the new health care plan and he said he would. Alext Karrus said too many jobs have been sent around the world.

title: Word on the Street: Expectations for New Congress?
description: We asked six people what their expectations were for the 112th congressional session which convened on Wednesday. Jan. 5. One responder thought it too soon to tell while another was uncertain of which direction the government would head in. The question was posed at McCaffrey's Supermarket in Yardley on Thursday. Jan. 6. 2011.

title: Word on the Street: Expectations for New Congress?
description: We asked six people what their expectations were for the 112th congressional session which convened on Wednesday. Jan. 5. One responder thought it too soon to tell while another was uncertain of the direction in which the government would head. The question was posed at McCaffrey's Supermarket in Yardley on Thursday. Jan. 6. 2011.

title: Operation Green Friends begins at Friends Village
description: Jeremy Wortzel and the Environmental Action Club of Council Rock High School North work with seniors to make Friends Village in Newtown Township more environmentally friendly. "...we would like to help reduce the energy cost for Friends Village." Wortzel said.

title: State Rep. Steve Santarsiero on issues and plans
description: State Representative Steve Santarsiero (D - 31) discusses the issues that currently face Pennsylvania and voices his opinion. He mentions education. jobs and the economy. natural gas drilling and outlines the legislation he intends to present in the new congressional session.

title: Snowfall in Newtown Borough
description: Old Man Winter added another several inches of snow to the ground on Saturday making for slippery travel. Here are some scenes shot as the snow quietly fell from the sky along State Street. Centre Avenue and Court Street in Newtown.

title: Word on the Street: Response to Arizona Shootings
description: For this week's Word on the Street we asked nine people on Newtown's State Street what their reaction was to the shootings of Arizona State Representative Gabrielle Giffords and others on Saturday. Jan. 8. All those who responded were horrified by the incident. many were also curious as to the motivation of the attack. The question was posed on Monday. Jan. 10. 2011.

title: Horse Thieves back in Yardley
description: The Yardleyville Protective Company holds its 144th Annual General Meeting and Dinner at the Yardley Country Club. The century-and-a-half old organization honors a member for distinguished community service in a "hanging" and celebrates. "This is a long term tradition and we hope to keep it going for as long as we possibly can." said Ray Naylor. President Elect of the company.

title: George School dance focues on special needs
description: Kevin Simone. Amanda Walters. Dan Kolbman and Paul Kim. seniors at George School. are working together with the Miracle League. a nationwide organization which allows indivieduals withy special needs to play sports regardless of their ability. Robin and Jim Young of Churchville brought their daughter. Heather. to a school dance so she could meet other athletes with special needs.

title: Students from Council Rock in MLK Day of Service
description: Students from the Council Rock school district participate in a day of service in honor of Martin Luther King Jr. Day.

title: Lt. Governor James Cawley on future and past
description: Newly elected Lt. Governor James Cawley speaks on his intentions in Harrisburg and his past term as a County Commissioner.

title: Inside The Brother's Moon in Hopewell
description: The Brother's Moon in Hopewell offers fine food in a relaxed atmosphere. Chef Will Mooney discusses what makes the restaurant unique and his experiences as a cook.

title: Guardians fete cemetery's first anniversary
description: The Guardians of the National Cemetery celebrated the first anniversary of the Washington Crossing National Cemegery on Thursday. Jan. 20 at its First Annual Volunteer Awards Dinner at Kings Caterers in Bristol Township. Fred Caldwell of Churchville was presented the "Number One Award" who since 2004 has consistently been the first to volunteer. whenever volunteers have been needed.

title: Hopewell Valley Faculty Musicale 2011
